did.unittitle: Men of Note library and scrapbooks
did.abstract: The Men of Note library and scrapbooks (dated 1987-2005, undated; 8.45 cubic feet, 9 boxes) comprise 390 dance band/big band sheet music sets and two scrapbooks used by or created by the Men of Note, a Lexington, Kentucky big band in operation from 1967-2009.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Collection is open to researchers by appointment.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Collection is arranged by format in two series: Sheet Music and Scrapbooks.

bioghist.head: Historical note
bioghist.p: The Men of Note were a Lexington big band that operated from 1967-2009. The band began as a group of friends meeting to casually play and bond over their love of music, but the group would go on to play a combination of prestigious and local gigs throughout central Kentucky, as well as at the Greenbrier Inn in White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia. Big band music enjoyed a revival during the 1990s that the group also benefited from, playing more than two dozen gigs per year at the height of their popularity. While primarily comprised of senior members, musicians of all ages joined the Men of Note over the course of its 42-year run. The Men of Note ultimately disbanded in 2009 due to a decline in performance bookings, as well as an inability to recruit enough young musicians to keep the group going.
Source: Rich Copley, Men of Note plays its last notes, Lexington Herald-Leader, Lexington, Kentucky, 2009 Augusst 16, Page 39. Newspapers.com, accessed November 15, 2022.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Men of Note library and scrapbooks (dated 1987-2005, undated; 8.45 cubic feet; 9 boxes) comprise 390 dance band/big band sheet music sets and two scrapbooks used by or created by the Men of Note, a Lexington, Kentucky big band in operation from 1967-2009. These are sets of instrumental parts (usually five saxophones, four trumpets, four trombones, and a rhythm section of piano, guitar, bass, and drums) required to play individual swing, ballad, Latin, blues, or other popular music tunes. Roughly 2/3 are published and 1/3 are manuscript arrangements by local band leaders, staff arrangers, or musicians. A majority of the published titles are out of print. Titles were passed down/came from not just the Men of Note (1967-2009), but also from five other Lexington dance band/big bands/jazz orchestras dating from 1943-1960. Scrapbooks include chart lists organized in a variety of ways (by type, by featured instrument, by who made the tune popular), set lists, promotional and marketing material, newspaper clippings, and a few photographs.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: The physical rights to the materials in this collection are held by the University of Kentucky Libraries Special Collections Research Center.
